# Building Location-Based AR Content Discovery with PostGIS and Three.js

When you're building a platform where users drop 3D AR content anywhere in a city and others discover it by physically walking around, you quickly run into a problem that looks deceptively simple: *how do you efficiently query "what's near me right now" at scale, and how do you render it in 3D without destroying battery life on a mobile browser?*

This is the core technical problem we solved building CityCanvas — a social AR platform that treats the entire city as a UGC canvas. This post goes deep on two of the most interesting engineering decisions: spatial querying with PostGIS, and anchoring 3D Three.js objects to real-world GPS coordinates.

---

## The Spatial Query Problem

The naive approach to "find content near me" is to pull all content from the database and filter on the client. This works when you have 50 records. It breaks when you have 50,000 AR objects scattered across a city, and every user is pinging the server every few seconds as they walk.

The smarter approach is to push the geographic computation down to the database layer using PostGIS, PostgreSQL's spatial extension. Supabase ships with PostGIS enabled, which means you get full access to spatial indexing and geographic functions without running your own database.

### Storing Positions as Geography Types

First, the schema. Instead of storing latitude and longitude as plain floats, we store each AR object's position as a PostGIS `geography` type. The distinction between `geometry` and `geography` matters here: `geometry` uses a flat Cartesian plane, while `geography` accounts for the curvature of the Earth. For city-scale distances, this precision actually matters.

```sql
CREATE TABLE ar_objects (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users(id),
  title TEXT NOT NULL,
  content_type TEXT CHECK (content_type IN ('3d_model', 'text', 'photo')),
  content_url TEXT,
  position GEOGRAPHY(POINT, 4326) NOT NULL,
  altitude FLOAT DEFAULT 0,
  created_at TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT NOW(),
  is_public BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE
);

-- Critical: spatial index on the geography column
CREATE INDEX ar_objects_position_idx 
  ON ar_objects USING GIST(position);
```

The `GIST` index on the geography column is what makes proximity queries fast. Without it, every "find nearby" query becomes a sequential scan. With it, PostGIS can use a bounding box pre-filter before the exact distance calculation, reducing the search space dramatically.

### The Proximity Query

Now the actual query. We want everything within a configurable radius (say 200 meters) of the user's current GPS position:

```javascript
// supabaseClient.js
export async function fetchNearbyARObjects(latitude, longitude, radiusMeters = 200) {
  const userPoint = `POINT(${longitude} ${latitude})`;

  const { data, error } = await supabase.rpc('get_nearby_ar_objects', {
    user_lat: latitude,
    user_lng: longitude,
    radius_m: radiusMeters,
  });

  if (error) throw error;
  return data;
}
```

And the corresponding PostgreSQL function:

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_nearby_ar_objects(
  user_lat FLOAT,
  user_lng FLOAT,
  radius_m FLOAT
)
RETURNS TABLE (
  id UUID,
  title TEXT,
  content_type TEXT,
  content_url TEXT,
  latitude FLOAT,
  longitude FLOAT,
  altitude FLOAT,
  distance_meters FLOAT
)
LANGUAGE SQL STABLE
AS $$
  SELECT
    id,
    title,
    content_type,
    content_url,
    ST_Y(position::geometry) AS latitude,
    ST_X(position::geometry) AS longitude,
    altitude,
    ST_Distance(
      position,
      ST_SetSRID(ST_MakePoint(user_lng, user_lat), 4326)::geography
    ) AS distance_meters
  FROM ar_objects
  WHERE
    is_public = TRUE
    AND ST_DWithin(
      position,
      ST_SetSRID(ST_MakePoint(user_lng, user_lat), 4326)::geography,
      radius_m
    )
  ORDER BY distance_meters ASC;
$$;
```

`ST_DWithin` is the key function here — it uses the spatial index efficiently, and returns only rows within the specified radius. `ST_Distance` then gives us the exact meter-accurate distance for sorting. Notice that longitude comes *before* latitude in `ST_MakePoint` — this is a common gotcha with PostGIS (it follows the GeoJSON convention of x,y = lng,lat).

---

## Bridging GPS Coordinates to Three.js World Space

This is where things get genuinely interesting. Three.js operates in its own Cartesian coordinate system. The origin is wherever you put it, units are arbitrary, and there's no inherent concept of "north" or "latitude." GPS coordinates are in decimal degrees, referencing an ellipsoidal Earth model. Getting a 3D object to appear exactly where it was placed in the real world requires a coordinate conversion layer.

### Local Tangent Plane Projection

The approach we use is a local East-North-Up (ENU) tangent plane projection. The idea: pick a reference point (the user's current position), then express every other point as a relative offset in meters along the east, north, and up axes. For the scale of an AR scene — typically within a few hundred meters — this flat-earth approximation is accurate enough. Error accumulates beyond ~1km, but by then you'd be loading a different set of objects anyway.

```javascript
// coordinateUtils.js

const EARTH_RADIUS_M = 6378137; // WGS-84 semi-major axis

/**
 * Convert GPS coordinates to Three.js world space relative to an origin point.
 * Returns { x, y, z } where:
 *   x = East offset in meters
 *   y = Up offset (altitude difference) in meters  
 *   z = -North offset in meters (Three.js uses right-handed coordinate system)
 */
export function gpsToWorldSpace(
  targetLat,
  targetLng,
  targetAlt,
  originLat,
  originLng,
  originAlt = 0
) {
  const dLat = ((targetLat - originLat) * Math.PI) / 180;
  const dLng = ((targetLng - originLng) * Math.PI) / 180;

  // At the origin latitude, scale longitude degrees to meters
  const cosLat = Math.cos((originLat * Math.PI) / 180);

  const northMeters = dLat * EARTH_RADIUS_M;
  const eastMeters = dLng * EARTH_RADIUS_M * cosLat;
  const upMeters = (targetAlt || 0) - originAlt;

  return {
    x: eastMeters,
    y: upMeters,
    z: -northMeters, // Three.js Z is inverted relative to North
  };
}

/**
 * Inverse: convert Three.js world position back to GPS for saving user-placed objects
 */
export function worldSpaceToGps(
  worldX,
  worldY,
  worldZ,
  originLat,
  originLng,
  originAlt = 0
) {
  const cosLat = Math.cos((originLat * Math.PI) / 180);

  const dLat = (-worldZ / EARTH_RADIUS_M) * (180 / Math.PI);
  const dLng = (worldX / (EARTH_RADIUS_M * cosLat)) * (180 / Math.PI);

  return {
    latitude: originLat + dLat,
    longitude: originLng + dLng,
    altitude: originAlt + worldY,
  };
}
```

The negative sign on `northMeters` when assigning to `z` trips people up the first time. Three.js uses a right-handed coordinate system where positive Z points *toward the viewer* (i.e., south in our mapping). If you forget this, all your objects appear mirrored north-south.

### Using It in the Scene

When the user's GPS updates and we receive nearby objects from PostGIS, we convert them all relative to the current position and update the Three.js scene:

```javascript
// arScene.js (simplified)
import * as THREE from 'three';
import { gpsToWorldSpace } from './coordinateUtils';

class ARScene {
  constructor(canvas) {
    this.scene = new THREE.Scene();
    this.camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(70, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
    this.renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ canvas, alpha: true });
    this.objectMeshes = new Map(); // arObjectId -> THREE.Object3D
    this.originPosition = null;
  }

  setOrigin(latitude, longitude, altitude = 0) {
    this.originPosition = { latitude, longitude, altitude };
  }

  placeARObject(arObject) {
    if (!this.originPosition) return;

    const worldPos = gpsToWorldSpace(
      arObject.latitude,
      arObject.longitude,
      arObject.altitude,
      this.originPosition.latitude,
      this.originPosition.longitude,
      this.originPosition.altitude
    );

    let mesh = this.objectMeshes.get(arObject.id);

    if (!mesh) {
      // Create a placeholder while the real model loads
      const geometry = new THREE.SphereGeometry(0.3, 16, 16);
      const material = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x00ffff, emissive: 0x003333 });
      mesh = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);
      this.scene.add(mesh);
      this.objectMeshes.set(arObject.id, mesh);

      // Load actual content asynchronously
      if (arObject.content_type === '3d_model') {
        this.loadGLTFModel(arObject.id, arObject.content_url, worldPos);
      }
    }

    mesh.position.set(worldPos.x, worldPos.y, worldPos.z);
  }

  // When GPS updates, recompute all world positions relative to new origin
  onGPSUpdate(newLat, newLng, newAlt) {
    this.setOrigin(newLat, newLng, newAlt);
    for (const [id, mesh] of this.objectMeshes) {
      // Re-fetch stored GPS coords and reproject
      // (stored in a parallel Map in production code)
    }
  }
}
```

One important nuance: we re-project all object positions on every significant GPS update, rather than accumulating drift by only moving relative to the last update. GPS coordinates drift slightly even when standing still, and accumulated relative offsets would cause objects to slowly drift from their real-world anchors.

---

## The Altitude Problem (and Why We Cheat Slightly)

Altitude is the awkward third dimension. GPS altitude from a phone's sensor is notoriously inaccurate — typical consumer GPS has ~3 meter vertical accuracy on a good day, and a bad day can see 10-15 meter errors. For a ground-level AR experience, this means objects anchored at "ground level" could be floating 5 meters in the air or buried underground.

Our practical solution: when users place objects, we snap them to a calculated "ground level" altitude based on the device's barometric altitude (when available) or a fixed offset above the current GPS altitude. We also allow a manual Y-axis adjustment during placement. When rendering, objects placed at ground level are rendered at Y=0 relative to the camera's origin, regardless of the GPS altitude noise.

This is a UX compromise that sacrifices pure GPS accuracy for perceptual stability. An object that's consistently "at street level" is more usable than one that technically has a GPS-accurate altitude but appears to float or sink depending on atmospheric pressure.

---

## Device Orientation and Camera Alignment

Making the Three.js camera align with where the phone is actually pointing uses the `DeviceOrientationEvent` API, combining compass heading (alpha), tilt (beta), and roll (gamma) into a quaternion that drives the Three.js camera rotation.

```javascript
function handleDeviceOrientation(event) {
  const { alpha, beta, gamma } = event;
  if (alpha === null) return;

  // Convert Euler angles to quaternion
  // Order matters: Three.js uses 'YXZ' for device orientation
  const euler = new THREE.Euler(
    THREE.MathUtils.degToRad(beta),
    THREE.MathUtils.degToRad(-(alpha)), // compass heading, negated
    THREE.MathUtils.degToRad(-gamma),
    'YXZ'
  );

  camera.quaternion.setFromEuler(euler);
}

window.addEventListener('deviceorientation', handleDeviceOrientation, true);
```

On iOS, you need to request permission for `DeviceOrientationEvent` explicitly (it was made permission-gated in iOS 13). On Android, it works without permission but compass calibration can be poor in areas with magnetic interference.

---

## Performance Considerations for Mobile

Three.js on mobile requires discipline. A few hard-won lessons:

**Frustum culling matters a lot.** Three.js does this automatically for standard meshes, but if you load GLTF models with complex hierarchies, check that `frustumCulled = true` is set on all child meshes. We had a bug early on where loaded models had this disabled, causing the GPU to process geometry the camera couldn't even see.

**Texture atlasing for UI elements.** All the billboard labels floating above AR objects share a single texture atlas, cutting draw calls significantly compared to individual textures per label.

**Limit the active render radius.** We only render objects within 100 meters even though we query 200 meters from PostGIS. The outer 100m acts as a pre-loading buffer so objects pop in before the user reaches them, but are rendered only when close enough to be meaningful.

**`requestAnimationFrame` throttling on battery saver mode.** When `navigator.getBattery()` reports a low charge or charging = false below 20%, we drop from 60fps to 30fps. For an AR app where the "content" is mostly static 3D objects, 30fps is imperceptible to users.

---

## PWA and Capacitor: One Codebase, Two Deployment Paths

CityCanvas ships as both a PWA and a native app (via Capacitor). The AR camera and GPS access patterns are nearly identical between web and native — both use the browser's `getUserMedia` API for the camera feed and the Geolocation API for position.

Where Capacitor earns its keep: native push notifications for "someone added an AR object near you," access to the device's compass with higher refresh rates via native plugins, and better performance on the camera pipeline (the native layer can process frames at the GPU level before handing them to WebGL, reducing latency).

The coordinate conversion and Three.js rendering code is 100% shared. The platform-specific code is isolated in a thin adapter layer — roughly 200 lines total — that maps native plugin APIs to the same interface the web implementation uses.

---

## Wrapping Up

The stack that makes CityCanvas work — PostGIS for spatial queries, a local tangent plane for GPS-to-Three.js projection, device orientation for camera alignment, and a PostGIS RPC layer via Supabase — handles the core challenges of any location-anchored AR experience built on web technologies.

The PostGIS approach in particular is worth adopting early. Adding a spatial index and switching lat/lng floats to a `geography` type is a small upfront cost that becomes a massive advantage as the dataset grows. The alternative (client-side filtering, or worse, bounding box queries with float comparisons) creates technical debt that's painful to pay off later.

If you're building anything in the location-aware or AR space on web technologies, the primitives are more capable than most developers expect. The browser stack handles this workload well with the right architecture.

For a deeper walkthrough of the CityCanvas architecture — including the Meshy AI text-to-3D pipeline and how we handle content moderation for user-placed AR objects — I've written a more detailed guide at [my blog](https://mcw999.github.io/mcw999-hub/blog/city-canvas-guide/?utm_source=hashnode&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=city-canvas).
